{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bb4f5e601ffc1a64", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tPS4: Proxy-Supervised Joint Training for Real\n2\tTarget Speaker Extraction\n3\tWanyi Ning1,2 , Wei Zhou1 , Yingpeng Li1 , Yinshang Guo3 , Haitao Qian1 , Yiming Cheng1\n4\t\n5\tarXiv:2607.08111v1 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n6\t\n7\t1\n8\t\n9\tYijiahe AI, Nanjing, China\n10\t\n11\t2\n12\t\n13\tTianjin University, Tianjin, China\n14\tningwanyi@126.com\n15\t\n16\tAbstract—Training target speaker extraction (TSE) models\n17\tfor real conversational mixtures remains challenging because\n18\tlarge-scale training corpora and clean target speech for supervision are unavailable. We present PS4, a proxy-supervised\n19\ttraining framework for TSE in real conversational mixtures,\n20\twith two main contributions. First, we construct a large-scale\n21\tcorpus of 71,771 training samples derived from four public\n22\tdatasets, covering both Chinese and English scenarios. Each\n23\tsample contains an overlapping speech mixture, per-speaker\n24\tenrollment audio, a ground-truth transcript, and frame-level\n25\tvoice activity labels. Second, we propose a proxy-supervised joint\n26\ttraining strategy that fine-tunes a BSRNN-based TSE model\n27\tusing four complementary differentiable objectives: ASR crossentropy, speaker similarity, frame-level voice activity detection,\n28\tand perceptual audio quality. Starting from a publicly available\n29\tpre-trained checkpoint, only the BSRNN separator is updated\n30\tduring fine-tuning. On the REAL-T challenge1 leaderboard, PS4\n31\tranks 2nd overall, achieving the best speaker similarity and\n32\ttiming F1 among all submitted systems.\n33\tIndex Terms—target speaker extraction, proxy supervision,\n34\tjoint training, real conversational speech\n35\t\n36\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n37\tTarget speaker extraction (TSE) aims to isolate the speech\n38\tof a specific speaker from a multi-talker mixture given a\n39\tshort enrollment utterance as a reference [1]–[5]. It has attracted increasing interest as a core component of personalized\n40\tspeech interfaces, meeting transcription, and assistive hearing\n41\tsystems. State-of-the-art TSE models [6]–[10] have achieved\n42\timpressive results on standard benchmarks such as VoxCeleb\n43\t[11], WSJ0-2mix [12] and LibriMix [13]. However, these\n44\tbenchmarks are constructed by artificially mixing clean singlespeaker recordings. In contrast, real conversational recordings\n45\texhibit substantially different characteristics: reverberation,\n46\tbackground noise, device-specific distortions, and natural turntaking patterns that produce irregular overlap durations and\n47\tspeaker ratios [14]–[19]. Because clean reference signals for\n48\tindividual speakers are unavailable in real-world recordings,\n49\tit is not straightforward to apply conventional signal-level\n50\tsupervision like SI-SNR loss [6], [20] to train TSE models on\n51\tsuch data. As a result, existing TSE systems are predominantly\n52\ttrained on simulated mixtures and may degrade when deployed\n53\tin real conversational scenarios.\n54\tTo bridge the gap between simulated benchmarks and realworld deployment, REAL-T [19] was introduced as the first\n55\tbenchmark for evaluating TSE systems on real conversational\n56\t\n57\t3\n58\t\n59\tNanjing University, Nanjing, China\n60\t\n61\tmixtures. It provides carefully curated real multi-talker recordings with corresponding speaker enrollment utterances and\n62\tevaluation annotations, enabling systematic assessment of TSE\n63\tmodels under realistic acoustic conditions. However, REALT is solely an evaluation benchmark and does not provide a\n64\tmatched training corpus or clean target speech for supervision.\n65\tConsequently, existing TSE models, including the official\n66\tREAL-T baseline, still rely on simulated mixtures for training\n67\t[1], [2], [9], [19]. How to effectively leverage large-scale real\n68\tconversational recordings for TSE training therefore remains\n69\tan open challenge.\n70\tIn this paper, we present PS4, a proxy-supervised training\n71\tframework for target speaker extraction from real conversational recordings. Instead of relying on unavailable clean target\n72\tspeech, PS4 leverages multiple proxy supervision signals that\n73\tcan be obtained directly from real conversational data. Our\n74\tmain contributions are summarized as follows:\n75\t• We construct the first large-scale proxy-supervised training corpus, REAL-PS42 , by reformatting four public\n76\tmeeting and conversational speech datasets into a unified\n77\ttraining format compatible with the REAL-T benchmark\n78\t[19]. The resulting corpus contains 71,771 training samples covering both Chinese and English scenarios, providing overlapping speech mixtures, speaker enrollment\n79\tutterances, transcripts, and voice activity annotations.\n80\t• We propose a proxy-supervised joint optimization framework PS43 that enables TSE training with multiple\n81\tcomplementary differentiable objectives from linguistic,\n82\tspeaker, temporal, and perceptual perspectives while remaining fully compatible with gradient optimization.\n83\t• The experiment results on the REAL-T benchmark [19]\n84\tdemonstrate that PS4 significantly improves the official\n85\tbaseline under the challenge evaluation protocol, providing an effective and practical solution for training TSE\n86\tmodels directly on real conversational recordings.\n87\tII. REAL-PS4 C ORPUS\n88\tWe construct a large-scale proxy-supervised training corpus, termed REAL-PS4, from four publicly available real\n89\tconversational speech datasets: AISHELL-4 [17], AliMeeting\n90\t[15], AMI [14], and CHiME-6 [16]. As shown in Fig. 1,\n91\twe generate enrollment utterances and target-speaker training\n92\t2 https://huggingface.co/datasets/TaurenMountain/REAL-PS4\n93\t\n94\t1 https://real-tse.github.io/challenge/\n95\t\n96\t3 Our code is available at https://github.com/TaurenMountain/PS4.\n97\t\n98\t\fInput\n99\tDatasets\n100\tAISHELL-4\n101\t(ZH, Meeting)\n102\t\n103\tEnrollment Extraction\n104\t\n105\tIsolate\n106\tFilter &\n107\tSingle-Speaker\n108\tTruncate\n109\tKeep >5s non-silent.\n110\tRegions\n111\tCap at 10s.\n112\t\n113\tAliMeeting\n114\t(ZH, Meeting)\n115\t\n116\tEnrollment\n117\tUtterances\n118\t\n119\tMixture Audio\n120\t\n121\tIdentify Overlap\n122\tRegions\n123\t(≥2 speakers)\n124\t\n125\tSegment &\n126\tTruncate\n127\t\n128\tMixture\n129\t\n130\tBSRNN\n131\t\n132\t+\n133\tECAPA\n134\t\n135\tExtracted\n136\tSpeech\n137\t\n138\tOUTPUT:\n139\tREAL-PS4\n140\t\n141\tTarget Transcripts\n142\t\n143\tMerge <0.5s gaps.\n144\tCap at 30s.\n145\t\n146\tVAD Labels\n147\t\n148\tPS4 Training Algorithm\n149\tEnrollment\n150\t\n151\tTSE Model\n152\t\n153\t1. Target > 20%\n154\tduration.\n155\t2. Text ≥ 2\n156\tvalid chars.\n157\t\n158\tMixture Generation\n159\t\n160\tAMI\n161\t(EN, Meeting)\n162\t\n163\tCHiME-6\n164\t(EN, Dinner)\n165\t\n166\tQuality\n167\tFilter\n168\t\n169\tProxy-Supervised Backprop\n170\t\n171\tLinguistic\n172\t\n173\tWhisper Large-v3\n174\t\n175\tCross-Entropy Loss\n176\t\n177\tSpeaker\n178\t\n179\tResNet34\n180\t\n181\tHinge Ranking Loss\n182\t\n183\tTemporal\n184\t\n185\tFrame Energy\n186\t\n187\tBCE Loss\n188\t\n189\tPerceptual\n190\t\n191\tDNSMOS\n192\t\n193\tOVRL Loss\n194\t\n195\tTotal\n196\tLoss\n197\t∑\n198\t\n199\tIII. M ETHOD : PS4\n200\tWe propose PS4, a proxy-supervised training framework\n201\twith four complementary objectives from real conversational\n202\trecordings, illustrated in Figure 1. Our method leverages\n203\tsupervision signals readily available in REAL-PS4, including\n204\ttranscripts, speaker enrollment, diarization annotations. We\n205\tbuild upon the pretrained BSRNN-ECAPA model released\n206\tin the REAL-T open-source repository4 [19]. It comprises\n207\ta BSRNN separator [23] and a pretrained ECAPA-TDNN\n208\tspeaker encoder [24], initialized from a checkpoint pretrained\n209\ton VoxCeleb1 [11]. During training, we fine-tune only the\n210\tseparator while keeping the speaker encoder frozen.\n211\tWe jointly optimize the separator using four complementary\n212\tproxy supervision objectives, which constrain the extracted\n213\tspeech from linguistic, speaker, temporal and perceptual perspectives, respectively. The overall training objective is defined\n214\tas\n215\tL = λce LCE + λsim LSIM + λdns LDNSMOS + λvad LVAD ,\n216\t\n217\tFig. 1. The workflow of PS4, including Corpus Construction and model\n218\ttraining.\n219\t\n220\tsamples through two parallel processing branches, followed\n221\tby a final quality filtering stage.\n222\tEnrollment extraction. For each recording session, speaker\n223\tdiarization annotations are first used to identify regions where\n224\texactly one speaker is active. These single-speaker segments\n225\tare treated as candidate enrollment utterances. To ensure\n226\tsufficient speaker information, only non-silent segments longer\n227\tthan 5 s are retained, and up to five enrollment clips are\n228\tselected for each speaker within a session.\n229\tMixture generation. Mixture samples are constructed from\n230\toverlapping speech regions where two or more speakers are\n231\tsimultaneously active. Adjacent overlap regions separated by\n232\tless than 0.5 s are merged to avoid excessive fragmentation,\n233\twhile merged segments shorter than 5 s or longer than 100 s\n234\tare discarded. For each retained segment, the corresponding\n235\tmixture waveform is extracted from the original recording and\n236\tpeak-normalized. The target speaker’s transcript is obtained\n237\tfrom the original annotations after removing non-speech markers. In addition, frame-level voice activity detection (VAD)\n238\t[21] labels are generated by projecting the target speaker’s\n239\tdiarization intervals onto the extracted mixture segment, providing temporal supervision during training.\n240\tQuality filtering. Finally, several quality-control rules are\n241\tapplied to improve the reliability of the corpus. We retain only\n242\tsamples in which the target speaker occupies more than 20%\n243\tof the mixture duration and the cleaned transcript contains\n244\tat least two valid characters. Since Whisper [22] accepts at\n245\tmost 30 s of audio as input, mixture segments are truncated\n246\tto this duration. Enrollment utterances are further limited to\n247\t10 s to reduce GPU memory consumption during training. The\n248\tremaining samples constitute the final REAL-PS4 corpus.\n249\t\n250\t(1)\n251\t\n252\twhere λce , λsim , λdns , and λvad denote the corresponding loss\n253\tweights.\n254\tLinguistic supervision. The extracted speech should preserve the linguistic content of the target speaker. We therefore\n255\temploy a frozen Whisper large-v3 [22] model as a differentiable teacher and compute the cross-entropy loss [25] between\n256\tthe predicted token distribution and the ground-truth transcript:\n257\tLCE = CrossEntropy (logits(fWhisper (ŝ)), ytext ) ,\n258\t\n259\t(2)\n260\t\n261\twhere ŝ denotes the extracted waveform and ytext is the\n262\treference transcript. This objective encourages the separator\n263\tto produce speech that remains accurately recognizable while\n264\tallowing gradients to propagate through the differentiable\n265\tWhisper frontend.\n266\tSpeaker supervision. To preserve the target speaker identity while suppressing interfering speakers, we introduce a\n267\tspeaker similarity objective based on cosine-margin ranking.\n268\tSpecifically, the similarity between the extracted speech and\n269\tthe enrollment utterance is encouraged to exceed that between\n270\tthe original mixture and the enrollment by a predefined\n271\tmargin:\n272\tLSIM = E [max (0, m − (cos(ŝ, e) − cos(x, e)))] ,\n273\t\n274\t(3)\n275\t\n276\twhere e denotes the enrollment utterance, x is the input mixture, and m is the margin. Speaker embeddings are extracted\n277\tusing frozen ResNet345 speaker encoders [26]\n278\tTemporal supervision. The diarization annotations used\n279\tduring corpus construction naturally provide frame-level target\n280\tspeaker activity labels. We exploit this information as an\n281\tauxiliary temporal supervision by minimizing the binary crossentropy between the predicted frame-level speech activity of\n282\tthe extracted waveform and the target VAD labels:\n283\tLVAD = BCE (σ(Energy(ŝ)), yVAD ) ,\n284\t4 https://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/wenet/wesep pretrained models\n285\t5 https://modelscope.cn/datasets/wenet/wespeaker pretrained models\n286\t\n287\t(4)\n288\t\n289\t\f0.6\n290\t\n291\t0.6\n292\t\n293\t0.4\n294\tI -6 o\n295\t-4 g\n296\tELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\n297\tAISH AliM\n298\t\n299\t0.5\n300\t\n301\t0.4\n302\tI -6 o\n303\t-4 g\n304\tELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\n305\tAISH AliM\n306\t\n307\tPS4 (ours)\n308\t\n309\t3\n310\tTiming F1\n311\t\n312\t0.8\n313\t\n314\tBSRNN-TFMAP\n315\tDNSMOS OVRL\n316\t\n317\t0.7\n318\tSpeaker SIM\n319\t\n320\tTER\n321\t\n322\tBSRNN-EMB\n323\t1.0\n324\t\n325\t2\n326\t\n327\tI -6 o\n328\t-4 g\n329\tELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\n330\tAISH AliM\n331\t\n332\tTABLE II\n333\tR ESULTS ON REAL-T CHALLENGE LEADERBOARD ( VALIDATION SET ).\n334\t\n335\t0.900\n336\t0.875\n337\t0.850\n338\t0.825\n339\t0.800\n340\t\n341\tI -6 o\n342\t-4 g\n343\tELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\n344\tAISH AliM\n345\t\n346\tFig. 2. Per-dataset evaluation on the REAL-T development set across four\n347\tmetrics.\n348\tTABLE I\n349\tP ER - DATASET RESULTS OF PS4 ON THE REAL-T DEVELOPMENT SET.\n350\tDataset\n351\t\n352\tN\n353\t\n354\tTER↓\n355\t\n356\tSIM↑\n357\t\n358\tDNSMOS OVRL↑\n359\t\n360\tF1↑\n361\t\n362\tAISHELL-4\n363\tAliMeeting\n364\tAMI\n365\tCHiME-6\n366\tDipCo\n367\t\n368\t240\n369\t481\n370\t592\n371\t545\n372\t133\n373\t\n374\t0.567\n375\t0.440\n376\t0.388\n377\t0.552\n378\t0.476\n379\t\n380\t0.575\n381\t0.633\n382\t0.714\n383\t0.567\n384\t0.622\n385\t\n386\t3.156\n387\t3.369\n388\t3.549\n389\t3.305\n390\t3.340\n391\t\n392\t0.900\n393\t0.861\n394\t0.902\n395\t0.891\n396\t0.897\n397\t\n398\tOverall\n399\t\n400\t1991\n401\t\n402\t0.473\n403\t\n404\t0.631\n405\t\n406\t3.377\n407\t\n408\t0.888\n409\t\n410\twhere yVAD denotes the target speaker activity labels derived\n411\tfrom the diarization annotations. This objective encourages the\n412\tseparator to produce speech that is temporally consistent with\n413\tthe target speaker activity.\n414\tPerceptual supervision. Besides preserving linguistic and\n415\tspeaker information, the extracted speech should also exhibit\n416\tgood perceptual quality. We therefore employ a differentiable\n417\timplementation of DNSMOS [27] as an auxiliary objective,\n418\tLDNSMOS = −DNSMOSOVRL (ŝ),\n419\t\n420\t(5)\n421\t\n422\twhere DNSMOSOVRL denotes the overall perceptual quality\n423\tscore predicted by the DNSMOS model6 . This objective\n424\tdirectly encourages higher perceptual speech quality without\n425\trequiring clean reference signals.\n426\tIV. E XPERIMENTS\n427\tWe conduct experiments on the REAL-T [19] development\n428\tset, which contains 1,991 samples from five conversational\n429\tspeech corpora: AISHELL-4 [17], AMI [14], AliMeeting\n430\t[15], CHiME-6 [16], and DipCo [18]. We follow the official\n431\tREAL-T evaluation protocol and report four metrics: token\n432\terror rate (TER), speaker similarity (SIM), DNSMOS OVRL\n433\tperceptual quality, and timing F1 [19]. TER is minimized,\n434\twhile the remaining three metrics are maximized. We compare PS4 with the two BSRNN-based baseline systems released by the REAL-T challenge, namely BSRNN_TFMAP\n435\tand BSRNN_EMB. Both models are trained on simulated\n436\tmixtures and have not been adapted to real conversational\n437\trecordings. In addition to the development set, we also submit\n438\tour system to the official REAL-T leaderboard. Note that\n439\tthe challenge organizers updated the perceptual quality metric\n440\tfrom DNSMOS OVRL to DNSMOS-P808 [28] for the final\n441\tleaderboard evaluation. Therefore, we report DNSMOS-P808\n442\tscores for the leaderboard results.\n443\t6 https://github.com/microsoft/dns-challenge\n444\t\n445\tSystem\n446\t\n447\tTER↓\n448\t\n449\tF1↑\n450\t\n451\tSIM↑\n452\t\n453\tDNSMOS-P808↑\n454\t\n455\tMERL’s\n456\tPS4 (ours)\n457\tCARTSE’s\n458\t\n459\t0.613\n460\t0.639\n461\t0.651\n462\t\n463\t0.861\n464\t0.871\n465\t0.857\n466\t\n467\t0.538\n468\t0.565\n469\t0.544\n470\t\n471\t3.371\n472\t3.128\n473\t3.138\n474\t\n475\tBSRNN EMB\n476\tBSRNN TFMAP\n477\t\n478\t0.829\n479\t0.838\n480\t\n481\t0.829\n482\t0.829\n483\t\n484\t0.417\n485\t0.443\n486\t\n487\t2.875\n488\t2.756\n489\t\n490\tFig. 2 visualizes the per-dataset performance across all four\n491\tmetrics. PS4 consistently outperforms both baselines on every\n492\tsub-corpus, with the most pronounced gains on DNSMOS\n493\tOVRL, where the baseline systems score below 2.0 while\n494\tPS4 exceeds 3.1 on all five datasets. The TER improvements\n495\tare also consistent, with PS4 achieving lower error rates than\n496\tboth baselines across all sub-corpora. Table I reports the\n497\tdetailed per-dataset numerical results of PS4. AMI achieves\n498\tthe lowest TER of 0.388 and the highest SIM of 0.714, likely\n499\tbecause AMI recordings have relatively clean lapel microphone channels that benefit enrollment extraction. AISHELL4 shows the highest TER of 0.567, which we attribute to the\n500\tmore challenging far-field acoustic conditions and the higher\n501\tproportion of overlapping speech in that corpus. Across all\n502\tfive datasets, PS4 achieves consistent SIM improvements over\n503\tthe mixture baseline, confirming that the speaker similarity\n504\tranking loss effectively guides the TSE model to preserve\n505\ttarget speaker identity.\n506\tTable II shows the challenge leaderboard results on the\n507\tofficial validation set. PS4 ranks 2nd overall on the leaderboard\n508\twith a composite score of 3.25. Notably, PS4 achieves the best\n509\tF1 of 0.871 and the best SIM of 0.565 among all submitted\n510\tsystems, demonstrating superior speaker extraction accuracy\n511\tand identity preservation. Although the DNSMOS-P808 score\n512\tof 3.128 is slightly lower than the top-ranked MERL’s system, and TER is slightly higher, PS4 decisively outperforms\n513\tMERL’s on SIM and F1. These results confirm that our\n514\tfour proxy supervision objectives provide effective training\n515\tsignals for TSE in real conversational scenarios, particularly\n516\tfor linguistic accuracy and speaker identity preservation.\n517\tV. C ONCLUSION\n518\tIn this paper, we presented PS4, a proxy-supervised joint\n519\ttraining framework for target speaker extraction from real\n520\tconversational recordings. To address the lack of clean reference speech in real-world data, we constructed REALPS4, a large-scale training corpus derived from four public\n521\tdatasets, covering both Chinese and English scenarios. We\n522\tfurther proposed a joint optimization strategy that combines\n523\tfour complementary proxy objectives to supervise the TSE\n524\tmodel without requiring clean isolated speech. Experiments\n525\ton the REAL-T benchmark demonstrate that PS4 consistently\n526\toutperforms the official baselines across all five sub-corpora\n527\tand all four evaluation metrics. On the official challenge\n528\tleaderboard, PS4 achieves the best F1 and speaker similarity\n529\tscores among all submitted systems, ranking 2nd overall.\n530\t\n531\t\fThese results validate that proxy supervision provides an\n532\teffective and practical alternative to conventional signal-level\n533\ttraining for TSE in real conversational scenarios.\n534\tR EFERENCES\n535\t[1] Q. Wang, H. Muckenhirn, K. Wilson, P. Sridhar, Z. Wu, J. Hershey, R. A.\n536\tSaurous, R. J. Weiss, Y. Jia, and I. L. Moreno, “Voicefilter: Targeted\n537\tvoice separation by speaker-conditioned spectrogram masking,” arXiv\n538\tpreprint arXiv:1810.04826, 2018.\n539\t[2] S. He, H. Li, and X. Zhang, “Speakerfilter: Deep learning-based target\n540\tspeaker extraction using anchor speech,” in ICASSP 2020-2020 IEEE\n541\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n542\t(ICASSP). IEEE, 2020, pp. 376–380.\n543\t[3] K. Zmolikova, M. Delcroix, T. Ochiai, K. Kinoshita, J. Černockỳ, and\n544\tD. Yu, “Neural target speech extraction: An overview,” IEEE Signal\n545\tProcessing Magazine, vol. 40, no. 3, pp. 8–29, 2023.\n546\t[4] H. Sato, T. Ochiai, K. Kinoshita, M. Delcroix, T. Nakatani, and S. Araki,\n547\t“Multimodal attention fusion for target speaker extraction,” in 2021\n548\tIEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT). IEEE, 2021, pp.\n549\t778–784.\n550\t[5] Y. Liu, X. Liu, and J. Yamagishi, “Improving curriculum learning for\n551\ttarget speaker extraction with synthetic speakers,” in 2024 IEEE Spoken\n552\tLanguage Technology Workshop (SLT). IEEE, 2024, pp. 364–370.\n553\t[6] Y. Luo and N. Mesgarani, “Conv-tasnet: Surpassing ideal time–\n554\tfrequency magnitude masking for speech separation,” IEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and language processing, vol. 27, no. 8, pp.\n555\t1256–1266, 2019.\n556\t[7] Y. Luo, Z. Chen, and T. Yoshioka, “Dual-path rnn: Efficient long\n557\tsequence modeling for time-domain single-channel speech separation,”\n558\tin ICASSP 2020-2020 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n559\tSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2020, pp. 46–50.\n560\t[8] C. Subakan, M. Ravanelli, S. Cornell, M. Bronzi, and J. Zhong,\n561\t“Attention is all you need in speech separation,” in ICASSP 20212021 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\n562\tProcessing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2021, pp. 21–25.\n563\t[9] B. Zeng and M. Li, “Usef-tse: Universal speaker embedding free target\n564\tspeaker extraction,” IEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech and Language\n565\tProcessing, 2025.\n566\t[10] T. Ling, S. He, P. Shen, and Z.-Q. Wang, “Mc-lext: Multi-channel\n567\ttarget speaker extraction with onset-prompted speaker conditioning\n568\tmechanism,” in ICASSP 2026-2026 IEEE International Conference on\n569\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2026, pp.\n570\t18 967–18 971.\n571\t[11] A. Nagrani, J. S. Chung, and A. Zisserman, “Voxceleb: a large-scale\n572\tspeaker identification dataset,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1706.08612, 2017.\n573\t[12] J. R. Hershey, Z. Chen, J. Le Roux, and S. Watanabe, “Deep clustering:\n574\tDiscriminative embeddings for segmentation and separation,” in 2016\n575\tIEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2016, pp. 31–35.\n576\t[13] J. Cosentino, M. Pariente, S. Cornell, A. Deleforge, and E. Vincent,\n577\t“Librimix: An open-source dataset for generalizable speech separation,”\n578\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2005.11262, 2020.\n579\t[14] J. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain,\n580\tJ. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal et al., “The ami\n581\tmeeting corpus: A pre-announcement,” in International workshop on\n582\tmachine learning for multimodal interaction. Springer, 2005, pp. 28–\n583\t39.\n584\t[15] F. Yu, S. Zhang, Y. Fu, L. Xie, S. Zheng, Z. Du, W. Huang, P. Guo,\n585\tZ. Yan, B. Ma et al., “M2met: The icassp 2022 multi-channel multiparty meeting transcription challenge,” in ICASSP 2022-2022 IEEE\n586\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n587\t(ICASSP). IEEE, 2022, pp. 6167–6171.\n588\t[16] S. Watanabe, M. Mandel, J. Barker, E. Vincent, A. Arora, X. Chang,\n589\tS. Khudanpur, V. Manohar, D. Povey, D. Raj et al., “Chime-6 challenge:\n590\tTackling multispeaker speech recognition for unsegmented recordings,”\n591\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2004.09249, 2020.\n592\t[17] Y. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu,\n593\tH. Bu et al., “Aishell-4: An open source dataset for speech enhancement,\n594\tseparation, recognition and speaker diarization in conference scenario,”\n595\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2104.03603, 2021.\n596\t[18] M. Van Segbroeck, A. Zaid, K. Kutsenko, C. Huerta, T. Nguyen, X. Luo,\n597\tB. Hoffmeister, J. Trmal, M. Omologo, and R. Maas, “Dipco–dinner\n598\tparty corpus,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1909.13447, 2019.\n599\t\n600\t[19] Shaole Li and Shuai Wang and Jiangyu Han and Ke Zhang and Wupeng\n601\tWang and Haizhou Li, “REAL-T: Real Conversational Mixtures for\n602\tTarget Speaker Extraction,” in Interspeech 2025, 2025, pp. 1923–1927.\n603\t[20] J. Le Roux, S. Wisdom, H. Erdogan, and J. R. Hershey, “Sdr–half-baked\n604\tor well done?” in ICASSP 2019-2019 IEEE International Conference on\n605\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2019, pp.\n606\t626–630.\n607\t[21] J. Sohn, N. S. Kim, and W. Sung, “A statistical model-based voice\n608\tactivity detection,” IEEE signal processing letters, vol. 6, no. 1, pp.\n609\t1–3, 1999.\n610\t[22] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\n611\tI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2212.04356, 2023.\n612\t[23] J. Yu, Y. Luo, H. Chen, R. Gu, and C. Weng, “High fidelity speech\n613\tenhancement with band-split rnn,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2212.00406,\n614\t2022.\n615\t[24] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “Ecapa-tdnn: Emphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in tdnn based\n616\tspeaker verification,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2005.07143, 2020.\n617\t[25] A. Mao, M. Mohri, and Y. Zhong, “Cross-entropy loss functions:\n618\tTheoretical analysis and applications,” in International conference on\n619\tMachine learning. pmlr, 2023, pp. 23 803–23 828.\n620\t[26] H. Wang, C. Liang, S. Wang, Z. Chen, B. Zhang, X. Xiang, Y. Deng,\n621\tand Y. Qian, “Wespeaker: A research and production oriented speaker\n622\tembedding learning toolkit,” in IEEE International Conference on\n623\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2023, pp.\n624\t1–5.\n625\t[27] C. K. Reddy, V. Gopal, and R. Cutler, “Dnsmos: A non-intrusive\n626\tperceptual objective speech quality metric to evaluate noise suppressors,”\n627\tin ICASSP 2021-2021 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n628\tSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2021, pp. 6493–6497.\n629\t[28] B. Naderi and R. Cutler, “An open source implementation of itu-t recommendation p. 808 with validation,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2005.08138,\n630\t2020.\n631\t\n632\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8e485752-f477-42b5-bc53-e4855d3db532", "uuid": "dfecead0-925c-4c4b-b8db-a22dae5385be", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T13:28:37.493Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/ps4_text.txt", "content": "PS4: Proxy-Supervised Joint Training for Real\nTarget Speaker Extraction\nWanyi Ning1,2 , Wei Zhou1 , Yingpeng Li1 , Yinshang Guo3 , Haitao Qian1 , Yiming Cheng1\n\narXiv:2607.08111v1 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n\n1\n\nYijiahe AI, Nanjing, China\n\n2\n\nTianjin University, Tianjin, China\nningwanyi@126.com\n\nAbstract—Training target speaker extraction (TSE) models\nfor real conversational mixtures remains challenging because\nlarge-scale training corpora and clean target speech for supervision are unavailable. We present PS4, a proxy-supervised\ntraining framework for TSE in real conversational mixtures,\nwith two main contributions. First, we construct a large-scale\ncorpus of 71,771 training samples derived from four public\ndatasets, covering both Chinese and English scenarios. Each\nsample contains an overlapping speech mixture, per-speaker\nenrollment audio, a ground-truth transcript, and frame-level\nvoice activity labels. Second, we propose a proxy-supervised joint\ntraining strategy that fine-tunes a BSRNN-based TSE model\nusing four complementary differentiable objectives: ASR crossentropy, speaker similarity, frame-level voice activity detection,\nand perceptual audio quality. Starting from a publicly available\npre-trained checkpoint, only the BSRNN separator is updated\nduring fine-tuning. On the REAL-T challenge1 leaderboard, PS4\nranks 2nd overall, achieving the best speaker similarity and\ntiming F1 among all submitted systems.\nIndex Terms—target speaker extraction, proxy supervision,\njoint training, real conversational speech\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nTarget speaker extraction (TSE) aims to isolate the speech\nof a specific speaker from a multi-talker mixture given a\nshort enrollment utterance as a reference [1]–[5]. It has attracted increasing interest as a core component of personalized\nspeech interfaces, meeting transcription, and assistive hearing\nsystems. State-of-the-art TSE models [6]–[10] have achieved\nimpressive results on standard benchmarks such as VoxCeleb\n[11], WSJ0-2mix [12] and LibriMix [13]. However, these\nbenchmarks are constructed by artificially mixing clean singlespeaker recordings. In contrast, real conversational recordings\nexhibit substantially different characteristics: reverberation,\nbackground noise, device-specific distortions, and natural turntaking patterns that produce irregular overlap durations and\nspeaker ratios [14]–[19]. Because clean reference signals for\nindividual speakers are unavailable in real-world recordings,\nit is not straightforward to apply conventional signal-level\nsupervision like SI-SNR loss [6], [20] to train TSE models on\nsuch data. As a result, existing TSE systems are predominantly\ntrained on simulated mixtures and may degrade when deployed\nin real conversational scenarios.\nTo bridge the gap between simulated benchmarks and realworld deployment, REAL-T [19] was introduced as the first\nbenchmark for evaluating TSE systems on real conversational\n\n3\n\nNanjing University, Nanjing, China\n\nmixtures. It provides carefully curated real multi-talker recordings with corresponding speaker enrollment utterances and\nevaluation annotations, enabling systematic assessment of TSE\nmodels under realistic acoustic conditions. However, REALT is solely an evaluation benchmark and does not provide a\nmatched training corpus or clean target speech for supervision.\nConsequently, existing TSE models, including the official\nREAL-T baseline, still rely on simulated mixtures for training\n[1], [2], [9], [19]. How to effectively leverage large-scale real\nconversational recordings for TSE training therefore remains\nan open challenge.\nIn this paper, we present PS4, a proxy-supervised training\nframework for target speaker extraction from real conversational recordings. Instead of relying on unavailable clean target\nspeech, PS4 leverages multiple proxy supervision signals that\ncan be obtained directly from real conversational data. Our\nmain contributions are summarized as follows:\n• We construct the first large-scale proxy-supervised training corpus, REAL-PS42 , by reformatting four public\nmeeting and conversational speech datasets into a unified\ntraining format compatible with the REAL-T benchmark\n[19]. The resulting corpus contains 71,771 training samples covering both Chinese and English scenarios, providing overlapping speech mixtures, speaker enrollment\nutterances, transcripts, and voice activity annotations.\n• We propose a proxy-supervised joint optimization framework PS43 that enables TSE training with multiple\ncomplementary differentiable objectives from linguistic,\nspeaker, temporal, and perceptual perspectives while remaining fully compatible with gradient optimization.\n• The experiment results on the REAL-T benchmark [19]\ndemonstrate that PS4 significantly improves the official\nbaseline under the challenge evaluation protocol, providing an effective and practical solution for training TSE\nmodels directly on real conversational recordings.\nII. REAL-PS4 C ORPUS\nWe construct a large-scale proxy-supervised training corpus, termed REAL-PS4, from four publicly available real\nconversational speech datasets: AISHELL-4 [17], AliMeeting\n[15], AMI [14], and CHiME-6 [16]. As shown in Fig. 1,\nwe generate enrollment utterances and target-speaker training\n2 https://huggingface.co/datasets/TaurenMountain/REAL-PS4\n\n1 https://real-tse.github.io/challenge/\n\n3 Our code is available at https://github.com/TaurenMountain/PS4.\n\n\fInput\nDatasets\nAISHELL-4\n(ZH, Meeting)\n\nEnrollment Extraction\n\nIsolate\nFilter &\nSingle-Speaker\nTruncate\nKeep >5s non-silent.\nRegions\nCap at 10s.\n\nAliMeeting\n(ZH, Meeting)\n\nEnrollment\nUtterances\n\nMixture Audio\n\nIdentify Overlap\nRegions\n(≥2 speakers)\n\nSegment &\nTruncate\n\nMixture\n\nBSRNN\n\n+\nECAPA\n\nExtracted\nSpeech\n\nOUTPUT:\nREAL-PS4\n\nTarget Transcripts\n\nMerge <0.5s gaps.\nCap at 30s.\n\nVAD Labels\n\nPS4 Training Algorithm\nEnrollment\n\nTSE Model\n\n1. Target > 20%\nduration.\n2. Text ≥ 2\nvalid chars.\n\nMixture Generation\n\nAMI\n(EN, Meeting)\n\nCHiME-6\n(EN, Dinner)\n\nQuality\nFilter\n\nProxy-Supervised Backprop\n\nLinguistic\n\nWhisper Large-v3\n\nCross-Entropy Loss\n\nSpeaker\n\nResNet34\n\nHinge Ranking Loss\n\nTemporal\n\nFrame Energy\n\nBCE Loss\n\nPerceptual\n\nDNSMOS\n\nOVRL Loss\n\nTotal\nLoss\n∑\n\nIII. M ETHOD : PS4\nWe propose PS4, a proxy-supervised training framework\nwith four complementary objectives from real conversational\nrecordings, illustrated in Figure 1. Our method leverages\nsupervision signals readily available in REAL-PS4, including\ntranscripts, speaker enrollment, diarization annotations. We\nbuild upon the pretrained BSRNN-ECAPA model released\nin the REAL-T open-source repository4 [19]. It comprises\na BSRNN separator [23] and a pretrained ECAPA-TDNN\nspeaker encoder [24], initialized from a checkpoint pretrained\non VoxCeleb1 [11]. During training, we fine-tune only the\nseparator while keeping the speaker encoder frozen.\nWe jointly optimize the separator using four complementary\nproxy supervision objectives, which constrain the extracted\nspeech from linguistic, speaker, temporal and perceptual perspectives, respectively. The overall training objective is defined\nas\nL = λce LCE + λsim LSIM + λdns LDNSMOS + λvad LVAD ,\n\nFig. 1. The workflow of PS4, including Corpus Construction and model\ntraining.\n\nsamples through two parallel processing branches, followed\nby a final quality filtering stage.\nEnrollment extraction. For each recording session, speaker\ndiarization annotations are first used to identify regions where\nexactly one speaker is active. These single-speaker segments\nare treated as candidate enrollment utterances. To ensure\nsufficient speaker information, only non-silent segments longer\nthan 5 s are retained, and up to five enrollment clips are\nselected for each speaker within a session.\nMixture generation. Mixture samples are constructed from\noverlapping speech regions where two or more speakers are\nsimultaneously active. Adjacent overlap regions separated by\nless than 0.5 s are merged to avoid excessive fragmentation,\nwhile merged segments shorter than 5 s or longer than 100 s\nare discarded. For each retained segment, the corresponding\nmixture waveform is extracted from the original recording and\npeak-normalized. The target speaker’s transcript is obtained\nfrom the original annotations after removing non-speech markers. In addition, frame-level voice activity detection (VAD)\n[21] labels are generated by projecting the target speaker’s\ndiarization intervals onto the extracted mixture segment, providing temporal supervision during training.\nQuality filtering. Finally, several quality-control rules are\napplied to improve the reliability of the corpus. We retain only\nsamples in which the target speaker occupies more than 20%\nof the mixture duration and the cleaned transcript contains\nat least two valid characters. Since Whisper [22] accepts at\nmost 30 s of audio as input, mixture segments are truncated\nto this duration. Enrollment utterances are further limited to\n10 s to reduce GPU memory consumption during training. The\nremaining samples constitute the final REAL-PS4 corpus.\n\n(1)\n\nwhere λce , λsim , λdns , and λvad denote the corresponding loss\nweights.\nLinguistic supervision. The extracted speech should preserve the linguistic content of the target speaker. We therefore\nemploy a frozen Whisper large-v3 [22] model as a differentiable teacher and compute the cross-entropy loss [25] between\nthe predicted token distribution and the ground-truth transcript:\nLCE = CrossEntropy (logits(fWhisper (ŝ)), ytext ) ,\n\n(2)\n\nwhere ŝ denotes the extracted waveform and ytext is the\nreference transcript. This objective encourages the separator\nto produce speech that remains accurately recognizable while\nallowing gradients to propagate through the differentiable\nWhisper frontend.\nSpeaker supervision. To preserve the target speaker identity while suppressing interfering speakers, we introduce a\nspeaker similarity objective based on cosine-margin ranking.\nSpecifically, the similarity between the extracted speech and\nthe enrollment utterance is encouraged to exceed that between\nthe original mixture and the enrollment by a predefined\nmargin:\nLSIM = E [max (0, m − (cos(ŝ, e) − cos(x, e)))] ,\n\n(3)\n\nwhere e denotes the enrollment utterance, x is the input mixture, and m is the margin. Speaker embeddings are extracted\nusing frozen ResNet345 speaker encoders [26]\nTemporal supervision. The diarization annotations used\nduring corpus construction naturally provide frame-level target\nspeaker activity labels. We exploit this information as an\nauxiliary temporal supervision by minimizing the binary crossentropy between the predicted frame-level speech activity of\nthe extracted waveform and the target VAD labels:\nLVAD = BCE (σ(Energy(ŝ)), yVAD ) ,\n4 https://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/wenet/wesep pretrained models\n5 https://modelscope.cn/datasets/wenet/wespeaker pretrained models\n\n(4)\n\n\f0.6\n\n0.6\n\n0.4\nI -6 o\n-4 g\nELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\nAISH AliM\n\n0.5\n\n0.4\nI -6 o\n-4 g\nELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\nAISH AliM\n\nPS4 (ours)\n\n3\nTiming F1\n\n0.8\n\nBSRNN-TFMAP\nDNSMOS OVRL\n\n0.7\nSpeaker SIM\n\nTER\n\nBSRNN-EMB\n1.0\n\n2\n\nI -6 o\n-4 g\nELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\nAISH AliM\n\nTABLE II\nR ESULTS ON REAL-T CHALLENGE LEADERBOARD ( VALIDATION SET ).\n\n0.900\n0.875\n0.850\n0.825\n0.800\n\nI -6 o\n-4 g\nELL eetin AMCHiME DipC\nAISH AliM\n\nFig. 2. Per-dataset evaluation on the REAL-T development set across four\nmetrics.\nTABLE I\nP ER - DATASET RESULTS OF PS4 ON THE REAL-T DEVELOPMENT SET.\nDataset\n\nN\n\nTER↓\n\nSIM↑\n\nDNSMOS OVRL↑\n\nF1↑\n\nAISHELL-4\nAliMeeting\nAMI\nCHiME-6\nDipCo\n\n240\n481\n592\n545\n133\n\n0.567\n0.440\n0.388\n0.552\n0.476\n\n0.575\n0.633\n0.714\n0.567\n0.622\n\n3.156\n3.369\n3.549\n3.305\n3.340\n\n0.900\n0.861\n0.902\n0.891\n0.897\n\nOverall\n\n1991\n\n0.473\n\n0.631\n\n3.377\n\n0.888\n\nwhere yVAD denotes the target speaker activity labels derived\nfrom the diarization annotations. This objective encourages the\nseparator to produce speech that is temporally consistent with\nthe target speaker activity.\nPerceptual supervision. Besides preserving linguistic and\nspeaker information, the extracted speech should also exhibit\ngood perceptual quality. We therefore employ a differentiable\nimplementation of DNSMOS [27] as an auxiliary objective,\nLDNSMOS = −DNSMOSOVRL (ŝ),\n\n(5)\n\nwhere DNSMOSOVRL denotes the overall perceptual quality\nscore predicted by the DNSMOS model6 . This objective\ndirectly encourages higher perceptual speech quality without\nrequiring clean reference signals.\nIV. E XPERIMENTS\nWe conduct experiments on the REAL-T [19] development\nset, which contains 1,991 samples from five conversational\nspeech corpora: AISHELL-4 [17], AMI [14], AliMeeting\n[15], CHiME-6 [16], and DipCo [18]. We follow the official\nREAL-T evaluation protocol and report four metrics: token\nerror rate (TER), speaker similarity (SIM), DNSMOS OVRL\nperceptual quality, and timing F1 [19]. TER is minimized,\nwhile the remaining three metrics are maximized. We compare PS4 with the two BSRNN-based baseline systems released by the REAL-T challenge, namely BSRNN_TFMAP\nand BSRNN_EMB. Both models are trained on simulated\nmixtures and have not been adapted to real conversational\nrecordings. In addition to the development set, we also submit\nour system to the official REAL-T leaderboard. Note that\nthe challenge organizers updated the perceptual quality metric\nfrom DNSMOS OVRL to DNSMOS-P808 [28] for the final\nleaderboard evaluation. Therefore, we report DNSMOS-P808\nscores for the leaderboard results.\n6 https://github.com/microsoft/dns-challenge\n\nSystem\n\nTER↓\n\nF1↑\n\nSIM↑\n\nDNSMOS-P808↑\n\nMERL’s\nPS4 (ours)\nCARTSE’s\n\n0.613\n0.639\n0.651\n\n0.861\n0.871\n0.857\n\n0.538\n0.565\n0.544\n\n3.371\n3.128\n3.138\n\nBSRNN EMB\nBSRNN TFMAP\n\n0.829\n0.838\n\n0.829\n0.829\n\n0.417\n0.443\n\n2.875\n2.756\n\nFig. 2 visualizes the per-dataset performance across all four\nmetrics. PS4 consistently outperforms both baselines on every\nsub-corpus, with the most pronounced gains on DNSMOS\nOVRL, where the baseline systems score below 2.0 while\nPS4 exceeds 3.1 on all five datasets. The TER improvements\nare also consistent, with PS4 achieving lower error rates than\nboth baselines across all sub-corpora. Table I reports the\ndetailed per-dataset numerical results of PS4. AMI achieves\nthe lowest TER of 0.388 and the highest SIM of 0.714, likely\nbecause AMI recordings have relatively clean lapel microphone channels that benefit enrollment extraction. AISHELL4 shows the highest TER of 0.567, which we attribute to the\nmore challenging far-field acoustic conditions and the higher\nproportion of overlapping speech in that corpus. Across all\nfive datasets, PS4 achieves consistent SIM improvements over\nthe mixture baseline, confirming that the speaker similarity\nranking loss effectively guides the TSE model to preserve\ntarget speaker identity.\nTable II shows the challenge leaderboard results on the\nofficial validation set. PS4 ranks 2nd overall on the leaderboard\nwith a composite score of 3.25. Notably, PS4 achieves the best\nF1 of 0.871 and the best SIM of 0.565 among all submitted\nsystems, demonstrating superior speaker extraction accuracy\nand identity preservation. Although the DNSMOS-P808 score\nof 3.128 is slightly lower than the top-ranked MERL’s system, and TER is slightly higher, PS4 decisively outperforms\nMERL’s on SIM and F1. These results confirm that our\nfour proxy supervision objectives provide effective training\nsignals for TSE in real conversational scenarios, particularly\nfor linguistic accuracy and speaker identity preservation.\nV. C ONCLUSION\nIn this paper, we presented PS4, a proxy-supervised joint\ntraining framework for target speaker extraction from real\nconversational recordings. To address the lack of clean reference speech in real-world data, we constructed REALPS4, a large-scale training corpus derived from four public\ndatasets, covering both Chinese and English scenarios. We\nfurther proposed a joint optimization strategy that combines\nfour complementary proxy objectives to supervise the TSE\nmodel without requiring clean isolated speech. Experiments\non the REAL-T benchmark demonstrate that PS4 consistently\noutperforms the official baselines across all five sub-corpora\nand all four evaluation metrics. On the official challenge\nleaderboard, PS4 achieves the best F1 and speaker similarity\nscores among all submitted systems, ranking 2nd overall.\n\n\fThese results validate that proxy supervision provides an\neffective and practical alternative to conventional signal-level\ntraining for TSE in real conversational scenarios.\nR EFERENCES\n[1] Q. Wang, H. Muckenhirn, K. Wilson, P. Sridhar, Z. Wu, J. Hershey, R. A.\nSaurous, R. J. Weiss, Y. Jia, and I. L. Moreno, “Voicefilter: Targeted\nvoice separation by speaker-conditioned spectrogram masking,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:1810.04826, 2018.\n[2] S. He, H. Li, and X. Zhang, “Speakerfilter: Deep learning-based target\nspeaker extraction using anchor speech,” in ICASSP 2020-2020 IEEE\nInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP). IEEE, 2020, pp. 376–380.\n[3] K. Zmolikova, M. Delcroix, T. Ochiai, K. Kinoshita, J. Černockỳ, and\nD. Yu, “Neural target speech extraction: An overview,” IEEE Signal\nProcessing Magazine, vol. 40, no. 3, pp. 8–29, 2023.\n[4] H. Sato, T. Ochiai, K. Kinoshita, M. Delcroix, T. Nakatani, and S. Araki,\n“Multimodal attention fusion for target speaker extraction,” in 2021\nIEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT). IEEE, 2021, pp.\n778–784.\n[5] Y. Liu, X. Liu, and J. Yamagishi, “Improving curriculum learning for\ntarget speaker extraction with synthetic speakers,” in 2024 IEEE Spoken\nLanguage Technology Workshop (SLT). IEEE, 2024, pp. 364–370.\n[6] Y. Luo and N. Mesgarani, “Conv-tasnet: Surpassing ideal time–\nfrequency magnitude masking for speech separation,” IEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and language processing, vol. 27, no. 8, pp.\n1256–1266, 2019.\n[7] Y. Luo, Z. Chen, and T. Yoshioka, “Dual-path rnn: Efficient long\nsequence modeling for time-domain single-channel speech separation,”\nin ICASSP 2020-2020 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\nSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2020, pp. 46–50.\n[8] C. Subakan, M. Ravanelli, S. Cornell, M. Bronzi, and J. Zhong,\n“Attention is all you need in speech separation,” in ICASSP 20212021 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\nProcessing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2021, pp. 21–25.\n[9] B. Zeng and M. Li, “Usef-tse: Universal speaker embedding free target\nspeaker extraction,” IEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech and Language\nProcessing, 2025.\n[10] T. Ling, S. He, P. Shen, and Z.-Q. Wang, “Mc-lext: Multi-channel\ntarget speaker extraction with onset-prompted speaker conditioning\nmechanism,” in ICASSP 2026-2026 IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2026, pp.\n18 967–18 971.\n[11] A. Nagrani, J. S. Chung, and A. Zisserman, “Voxceleb: a large-scale\nspeaker identification dataset,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1706.08612, 2017.\n[12] J. R. Hershey, Z. Chen, J. Le Roux, and S. Watanabe, “Deep clustering:\nDiscriminative embeddings for segmentation and separation,” in 2016\nIEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2016, pp. 31–35.\n[13] J. Cosentino, M. Pariente, S. Cornell, A. Deleforge, and E. Vincent,\n“Librimix: An open-source dataset for generalizable speech separation,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2005.11262, 2020.\n[14] J. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain,\nJ. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal et al., “The ami\nmeeting corpus: A pre-announcement,” in International workshop on\nmachine learning for multimodal interaction. Springer, 2005, pp. 28–\n39.\n[15] F. Yu, S. Zhang, Y. Fu, L. Xie, S. Zheng, Z. Du, W. Huang, P. Guo,\nZ. Yan, B. Ma et al., “M2met: The icassp 2022 multi-channel multiparty meeting transcription challenge,” in ICASSP 2022-2022 IEEE\nInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP). IEEE, 2022, pp. 6167–6171.\n[16] S. Watanabe, M. Mandel, J. Barker, E. Vincent, A. Arora, X. Chang,\nS. Khudanpur, V. Manohar, D. Povey, D. Raj et al., “Chime-6 challenge:\nTackling multispeaker speech recognition for unsegmented recordings,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2004.09249, 2020.\n[17] Y. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu,\nH. Bu et al., “Aishell-4: An open source dataset for speech enhancement,\nseparation, recognition and speaker diarization in conference scenario,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2104.03603, 2021.\n[18] M. Van Segbroeck, A. Zaid, K. Kutsenko, C. Huerta, T. Nguyen, X. Luo,\nB. Hoffmeister, J. Trmal, M. Omologo, and R. Maas, “Dipco–dinner\nparty corpus,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1909.13447, 2019.\n\n[19] Shaole Li and Shuai Wang and Jiangyu Han and Ke Zhang and Wupeng\nWang and Haizhou Li, “REAL-T: Real Conversational Mixtures for\nTarget Speaker Extraction,” in Interspeech 2025, 2025, pp. 1923–1927.\n[20] J. Le Roux, S. Wisdom, H. Erdogan, and J. R. Hershey, “Sdr–half-baked\nor well done?” in ICASSP 2019-2019 IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2019, pp.\n626–630.\n[21] J. Sohn, N. S. Kim, and W. Sung, “A statistical model-based voice\nactivity detection,” IEEE signal processing letters, vol. 6, no. 1, pp.\n1–3, 1999.\n[22] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\nI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2212.04356, 2023.\n[23] J. Yu, Y. Luo, H. Chen, R. Gu, and C. Weng, “High fidelity speech\nenhancement with band-split rnn,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2212.00406,\n2022.\n[24] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “Ecapa-tdnn: Emphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in tdnn based\nspeaker verification,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2005.07143, 2020.\n[25] A. Mao, M. Mohri, and Y. Zhong, “Cross-entropy loss functions:\nTheoretical analysis and applications,” in International conference on\nMachine learning. pmlr, 2023, pp. 23 803–23 828.\n[26] H. Wang, C. Liang, S. Wang, Z. Chen, B. Zhang, X. Xiang, Y. Deng,\nand Y. Qian, “Wespeaker: A research and production oriented speaker\nembedding learning toolkit,” in IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2023, pp.\n1–5.\n[27] C. K. Reddy, V. Gopal, and R. Cutler, “Dnsmos: A non-intrusive\nperceptual objective speech quality metric to evaluate noise suppressors,”\nin ICASSP 2021-2021 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\nSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2021, pp. 6493–6497.\n[28] B. Naderi and R. Cutler, “An open source implementation of itu-t recommendation p. 808 with validation,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2005.08138,\n2020.\n\n\f", "numLines": 632, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 632}}}
